etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in John Florio (1553–1625), author and teacher of languages. From out- + runner

definitions: A person who or animal which runs along the outside or outer side of something, as an attendant who runs ahead of or beside a carriage, a dog leading a team of sledge dogs, etc. Also figurative: one who goes about gathering or spreading intelligence; a forerunner, an advance party (now chiefly historical).
A projection or outshoot of a forest, mountain range, or some other physical feature.
A person who or thing which outruns something.

notes.text: "outrunner of the constable": one who exceeds all sensible limits in behaviour, expenditure, etc.
